00:00:20.168 --> 00:00:21.710
WILLIAM B. BONVILLIAN:
I'm just going

00:00:21.710 --> 00:00:24.950
to go very quickly through
the World Economic Forum.

00:00:24.950 --> 00:00:28.190
I only wanted you all to glance
at this and get an idea of it,

00:00:28.190 --> 00:00:33.140
because what it's in here
for is to show that we're not

00:00:33.140 --> 00:00:35.660
the only ones trying to think
about innovation factors,

00:00:35.660 --> 00:00:35.900
right.

00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:37.317
They are trying
to figure out what

00:00:37.317 --> 00:00:40.730
these factors are as they assess
different national economies.

00:00:40.730 --> 00:00:43.550
They have a whole global
competitiveness rating

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:46.170
system, which they get
out every other year.

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:49.250
So in 2015, 2016, as
you saw, Switzerland

00:00:49.250 --> 00:00:50.840
was number one,
Singapore number two,

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:53.780
and the US was number
three in their rating.

00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:57.590
And then they have a
whole series of elements

00:00:57.590 --> 00:01:01.310
that they consider in their
global competitiveness

00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:01.980
analysis.

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:06.620
So they look at what they
call factor-driven economies,

00:01:06.620 --> 00:01:10.010
and the pillars there are
institutions and infrastructure

00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:13.640
and macroeconomic
environment and actually

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:16.550
early-stage education
as a pillar in health.

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:21.080
And then efficiency-driven
economies, they call them--

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:25.220
that's higher education, that's
market efficiency for goods,

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:27.980
that's labor market
efficiency, that's

00:01:27.980 --> 00:01:32.400
financial market developments,
technology readiness, and so

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:32.900
forth.

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:34.760
And then innovation-driven
economies,

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:37.910
business sophistication,
and innovation capability.

00:01:37.910 --> 00:01:39.890
So they have a very
different mix here.

00:01:39.890 --> 00:01:42.170
I just wanted to throw in
kind of a comparative way

00:01:42.170 --> 00:01:44.570
of other people
looking at the problems

00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:47.420
that we're talking about,
and the kind of pillars

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:49.010
that they come
about, and how they

00:01:49.010 --> 00:01:53.960
sort different kind of world
economies and organize them.

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:59.540
But a lot of these factors
we've just been talking about.

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:02.330
Kind of the core,
I think, of what

00:02:02.330 --> 00:02:08.240
the takeaway is from this
study, and let me get--

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:10.490
you also had Rycroft,
Lily, as well,

00:02:10.490 --> 00:02:15.590
so why don't I get Rycroft
out on the table too.

00:02:15.590 --> 00:02:17.540
That's Bob Rycroft and Kash.

00:02:21.170 --> 00:02:23.450
They did this
piece back in 1999.

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:29.620
And I'm leading in to how do
you look at some of these more

00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:33.220
indirect innovation factors?

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:35.320
Because they remain
important, and we're just

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:38.320
going to pick three.

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:42.820
And you know they're looking
at a kind of an element

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:45.460
of innovation organization,
which I think is a core factor,

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:48.340
but they're talking about
kind of a sub-piece of it,

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:52.930
this kind of networking theory
of innovation organization.

00:02:52.930 --> 00:02:57.020
I think it's an
intriguing piece.

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:00.140
They argue that we are now at
a stage in the world economy

00:03:00.140 --> 00:03:03.640
that complex technologies
drive the economy.

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:08.900
So with complex technologies,
the lone inventor

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:12.432
in the garage working solo--

00:03:12.432 --> 00:03:13.015
that's a myth.

00:03:13.015 --> 00:03:16.570
That doesn't work anymore,
because the technologies that

00:03:16.570 --> 00:03:19.930
lead to innovation are just
too complex, they argue.

00:03:19.930 --> 00:03:23.230
So that means that
the traditional focus

00:03:23.230 --> 00:03:28.510
of US technology policy on
R&D at particular institutions

00:03:28.510 --> 00:03:33.520
and in open markets, that's not
necessarily right anymore, they

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:34.810
argue.

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:38.680
So they say that a much
more self-conscious

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:44.610
networked learning
environment is actually key.

00:03:44.610 --> 00:03:47.690
And what does that mean?

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:52.670
Well, complex technologies, we
know, dominate world exports--

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:59.650
82% in 1995 compared
to 43% in 1970.

00:03:59.650 --> 00:04:02.110
The rise in complex
products means

00:04:02.110 --> 00:04:05.840
a rise in complex organizational
models that goes with it.

00:04:08.470 --> 00:04:10.060
The number of
corporate alliances,

00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:12.070
corporate interrelationships,
the connectedness

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:14.980
to the actors, becomes all
that much more critical

00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:19.930
when the dominant products
are complex technology based.

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:21.910
So as product complexity
grows, the need

00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:26.440
for innovative networks grows.

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:31.480
And technological
progress in this phase

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:34.480
really requires that network
learning, integrating,

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:36.370
and applying a
whole wide variety

00:04:36.370 --> 00:04:39.490
of new science and technology
knowledge and know-how.

00:04:39.490 --> 00:04:40.690
That now becomes key.

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:46.680
Gee whiz, you know, we're
not organized around that.

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:50.080
If these guys are right,
we've got an innovation system

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:53.590
that's organized on a
much earlier idea of how

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:55.240
technologies evolve.

00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:58.660
It doesn't necessarily reflect
the reality of the complexity,

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:00.370
and the fact that
the complexity drives

00:05:00.370 --> 00:05:04.870
much more complex organizational
system, which includes

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:07.190
networking, they argue.

00:05:07.190 --> 00:05:13.640
So they cite George Brown,
who is a great former chairman

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:16.850
of the House Science Committee,
on the point that neglect

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:19.700
of the processes of
knowledge and their diffusion

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:23.900
and application needs to be a
core concern of the innovation

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:24.400
system.

00:05:26.995 --> 00:05:28.620
And Brown is talking
about particularly

00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:33.100
at the governmental level, the
governmental kind of role here.

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:35.090
There's new kinds of
learning that need

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:39.030
to take place and need
to be organized around.

00:05:39.030 --> 00:05:41.360
If you're going
to have this kind

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:44.400
of learning network system--

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:46.830
so a shared network
learning, which

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:49.830
cuts across a series
of institutions,

00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:53.040
institutional
engineering that brings

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:55.620
in other parts of the systems,
like the regulatory side,

00:05:55.620 --> 00:05:58.550
into the network--

00:05:58.550 --> 00:06:00.780
there's got to be a
whole evaluation and what

00:06:00.780 --> 00:06:04.230
they call co-evaluation
between complex organizations

00:06:04.230 --> 00:06:06.420
and the technologies
that they're developing.

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:10.360
So learning by doing,
learning by using,

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:12.850
learning from scientific
and technology advances,

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:17.300
learning from spillovers,
learning from interaction.

00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:20.120
They argue that these are
whole new features of learning

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:22.287
that need to occur that
aren't necessarily accounted

00:06:22.287 --> 00:06:24.300
for our current
learning systems.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:26.690
So they need to be changed
to really accommodate

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:29.990
the new realities of the
way in which innovation is

00:06:29.990 --> 00:06:31.700
going to have to get organized.

00:06:31.700 --> 00:06:36.210
So that's their proposition.

00:06:36.210 --> 00:06:39.120
I thought it was just
kind of a fun read.

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:41.622
It tells us a little more
about the determinism piece

00:06:41.622 --> 00:06:43.080
that we were talking
about earlier,

00:06:43.080 --> 00:06:47.250
complex technologies demand
new organizational models.

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:49.980
And if Nelson is right,
innovation organization really

00:06:49.980 --> 00:06:54.070
amounts to a core direct
innovation factor,

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:57.660
then you know stuff like what
Rycroft and Kash are proposing

00:06:57.660 --> 00:06:59.620
becomes significant
in the process.

