00:24:02.950 --> 00:24:09.580
Venture capital, by 1999,
had grown from $3 billion

00:24:09.580 --> 00:24:12.460
at the beginning of the
decade to $30 billion.

00:24:12.460 --> 00:24:16.690
Now venture capital in
2015 was $60 billion.

00:24:16.690 --> 00:24:19.540
So venture capital
was built on the idea

00:24:19.540 --> 00:24:21.460
that introducing
new technologies

00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:24.472
delivers much higher
investor returns.

00:24:24.472 --> 00:24:25.930
Remember that chart
that one of you

00:24:25.930 --> 00:24:28.680
cleverly asked me how many
years it covered, was that--

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:31.270
that was Martin?

00:24:31.270 --> 00:24:33.220
This is, he's saying
the same thing.

00:24:33.220 --> 00:24:36.190
In other words,
if you can capture

00:24:36.190 --> 00:24:40.942
the gains of radical investment,
they can be really big.

00:24:40.942 --> 00:24:42.400
And that's what
the venture capital

00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:43.600
sector is organized around.

00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:46.030
And he notes this
interesting history.

00:24:46.030 --> 00:24:49.420
So we're in one of the
capitals of venture capital,

00:24:49.420 --> 00:24:51.910
we're in the place
that originated it.

00:24:51.910 --> 00:24:56.170
The East Coast model originally
was much more focused

00:24:56.170 --> 00:25:00.260
on what we would call, today,
financial engineering--

00:25:00.260 --> 00:25:04.100
you know, tax benefits,
short term returns,

00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:09.860
that conceptual framework kind
of dominated the early Boston

00:25:09.860 --> 00:25:12.290
venture capital model.

00:25:12.290 --> 00:25:15.350
The West Coast developed
a very different model

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:19.220
around science and
technology-driven growth

00:25:19.220 --> 00:25:21.440
in places like Sand Hill
Road and Silicon Valley,

00:25:21.440 --> 00:25:22.790
it's still its capita.

00:25:22.790 --> 00:25:27.020
So now those distinctions
have pretty much disappeared.

00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:30.800
Both sides are in the same game.

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:33.830
And you include within the
term of venture capital,

00:25:33.830 --> 00:25:35.900
some people include a
much broader phraseology,

00:25:35.900 --> 00:25:40.700
including angel investors,
corporate venture firms,

00:25:40.700 --> 00:25:42.560
foundation venture
firms, sometimes

00:25:42.560 --> 00:25:44.180
university endowment
funds, that go

00:25:44.180 --> 00:25:45.520
to a venture kind of purpose.

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:51.110
So it's a bigger landscape than
it was at the early stages.

00:25:51.110 --> 00:25:53.510
But the East Coast
model, which did things

00:25:53.510 --> 00:25:56.600
like late-stage buyouts,
turnarounds, roll-UPS,

00:25:56.600 --> 00:26:00.110
consolidations, in addition
to early-stage venture.

00:26:00.110 --> 00:26:03.020
That's now prevalent, frankly,
in both the East Coast and West

00:26:03.020 --> 00:26:04.410
Coast models.

00:26:04.410 --> 00:26:06.380
So the two sides
have kind of merged.

00:26:06.380 --> 00:26:09.830
The originator of the
venture capital idea

00:26:09.830 --> 00:26:14.420
was General Georges Doriot,
who was World War II general,

00:26:14.420 --> 00:26:17.990
helped in the
organization of industry

00:26:17.990 --> 00:26:21.500
in Europe during World War
II and following it, so

00:26:21.500 --> 00:26:22.342
a remarkable figure.

00:26:22.342 --> 00:26:24.050
He taught at the
Harvard Business School,

00:26:24.050 --> 00:26:26.930
but he's the one who kind
of saw this potential gain

00:26:26.930 --> 00:26:28.775
from innovation-based growth.

00:26:28.775 --> 00:26:32.390
And the West Coast model really
was kind of a maverick model.

00:26:32.390 --> 00:26:35.750
It was very high-risk
investment based

00:26:35.750 --> 00:26:39.530
