00:59:08.390 --> 00:59:11.000
it's this technological
related innovation.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:14.960
So in a way you can see
Schultze, just as you suggest,

00:59:14.960 --> 00:59:19.100
as a dialogue within
different stages of economics

00:59:19.100 --> 00:59:19.940
thinking right.

00:59:19.940 --> 00:59:23.600
And Schultze, in many ways, is
certainly in the neoclassical

00:59:23.600 --> 00:59:26.750
and in a way earlier
classical economics

00:59:26.750 --> 00:59:29.840
thinking about growth,
before new growth theory

00:59:29.840 --> 00:59:33.890
develops from people
like Solow and Romer.

00:59:33.890 --> 00:59:35.610
So that's part of
what he's saying here.

00:59:35.610 --> 00:59:41.420
But I do think that his
point about the difficulty

00:59:41.420 --> 00:59:44.390
